DIA (
                     Fig. 1

                     ), chemically known as 4, 5- diacetyloxy-9, 10-dioxo-anthracene-2-carboxylic acid, is a prodrug belonging to the anthraquinone group and it is used for the management of osteoarthritis and other joint disorders because of the inhibition of the interleukin-1 beta, a protein implicated in cartilage inflammation and degradation that contributes to the onset of degenerative joint symptoms, it causes [1]. It is commonly co formulated with glucosamine sulfate (GLU) and methyl sulfonyl methane (MSM) which are chemically known as (2R, 3R, 4S, 5R)-2-Amino-3, 4, 5, 6-tetrahydroxyhexanal sulfate (2:1) and methyl sulfonyl methane, respectively. This combination of DIA, GLU and MSM is formulated as tablet at which DIA is present as a minor component and it is used for the management of osteoarthritis.

It is important to determine DIA in presence of the co formulated drugs in its combined tablet dosage form without occurrence of any interference, especially when DIA is a minor component. The developed sensing system was successfully applied for determination of the studied drug in presence of co formulated drugs with good selectivity and % recovery. The sample solutions were prepared as mentioned above under the experimental section and the DIA concentration was calculated from the regression equation. The obtained results were statistically compared with those obtained from the reported HPLC method [12] using student; 
                        t-test and variance ratio F-test and the results revealed that there was no significant difference between the performance of the two methods as shown in Table 4
                        . The good % recoveries illustrate the sensing system's reliability and selectivity for DIA in the presence of the co formulated drugs.
